    <section id="tribute-info">
        <h3>A breif timeline of Sir David David Attenborough:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>1926 </strong>
                - Born in London, United Kingdom
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>1945 </strong>
                - Recieved scholarship to Cambridge for degree in Natural Sciences
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>1950 </strong>
                - Married Jane Elizabeth Ebsworth Oriel (died 1997) whom he had 2 children with
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>1952 </strong>
                - Joined the BBC becoming producer for the Talks department
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>1957 </strong>
                - Formed the Travel and Exploration Unit
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>1965 </strong>
                - Became controller of BBC 2
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>1972 </strong>
                - Won his first award: Royal Geographical Society's Cherry Kearton Medal and Award
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>1973 </strong>
                - Made nature documentary series Eastwards with Attenborough after resigning from the BBC
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>1979 </strong>
                - Started famous Life on Earth documentary series
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>1984 </strong>
                - Released The Living Planet focusing on ecology
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>1990 </strong>
                - Released The Trials of Life focusing on animal behaviour
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>1996 </strong>
                -Awarded the Kew Internation Medal for his conservation efforts
            </li>
        </ul>
    <a id="tribute-link" target="_blank" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Attenborough">Wikipedia on Sir David Attenborough HERE!</a>
    </section>
